==History== The area comprising Huitzo was inhabited as early as 1200 [[BCE]]. By 1400 AD a [[Zapotec peoples|Zapotec]] village existed that was known by the name of ''Huijazoo'', a word that means ''Warrior Watchtower'' in the [[Zapotec language]].<ref name=Huitzo/> In 1522 Spanish troops arrived and founded the current city, giving it the name ''Gueixolotitlan''. However, by 1700 the name ''Huitzo'' had been adopted by the populace. When the first [[Roman Catholic]] monks arrived to [[evangelize]] the local population, they selected [[St. Paul the Apostle]] ''(San Pablo, in Spanish)'' as the [[patron saint]] of the village and erected a church by the same name. The church is notable for a large number of 16th-century and other colonial-era ''santos'', statues of the saints.<ref>[http://www.aug.edu/augusta/santos/huitzo/index.html Santos in Oaxaca's Ancient Churches: San Pablo Huitzo] Retrieved 2012-04-13</ref> It was through the influence of the Catholic Church that the town arrived at its present name San Pablo Huitzo.<ref name=Huitzo/>
==Modern day== [[File:Tomb in San Pablo Huitzo, Oaxaca.jpg|left|thumb|Post-classic era tomb in Huitzo]] Today Huitzo is a farming community noted for growing vegetables and flowers, with almost half of its population employed by farms or other agriculture-related ventures.<ref name=Huitzo/> Archaeological sites in the area consist of several tombs, walls, and similar Zapotec structures. Most of the sites are overgrown with vegetation, however they do attract some tourists and [[archaeologists]].<ref name=guide>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fJ8AAqwPTRoC&lpg=PA205&dq=%22Huitzo%22&pg=PA205#v=onepage&q=%22Huitzo%22&f=false|title=An archaeological guide to central and southern Mexico|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|author1=Kelly, Joyce |author2=Kelly, Jerry |accessdate=2010-11-11|isbn=0-8061-3349-X|year=2001}}</ref> {{Clear}}
